SIMPLE: scrub
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scrub
<hw>Scrub</hw> <pr>(skr⟦ucr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Scrubbed</conjf> <pr>(skr⟦ucr⟧bd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Scrubbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>scrobben</ets>, probably of Dutch or Scand. origin; cf. Dan.
<ets>skrubbe</ets>, Sw. <ets>skrubba</ets>, D. <ets>schrobben</ets>, LG.
<ets>schrubben</ets>.]</ety> <def>To rub hard; to wash with rubbing;
usually, to rub with a wet brush, or with something coarse or rough, for
the purpose of cleaning or brightening; <as>as, to <ex>scrub</ex> a
floor, a doorplate</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrub</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scrub
<hw>Scrub</hw> <pr>(skr⟦ucr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To rub
anything hard, especially with a wet brush; to scour; hence, to be
diligent and penurious; <as>as, to <ex>scrub</ex> hard for a
living</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrub</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scrub
<hw>Scrub</hw> <pr>(skr⟦ucr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One
who labors hard and lives meanly; a mean fellow.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A sorry
<xex>scrub</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bunyan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We should go there in as proper a manner as possible; nor
altogether like the <qex>scrubs</qex> about us.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something small and mean.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A worn-out brush.</def>
<rj><au>Ainsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A thicket or jungle, often specified by the name of
the prevailing plant; <as>as, oak <ex>scrub</ex>, palmetto
<ex>scrub</ex>, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Stock Breeding)</fld> <def>One of the common live
stock of a region of no particular breed or not of pure breed, esp. when
inferior in size, etc.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Vegetation of inferior quality, though sometimes
thick and impenetrable, growing in poor soil or in sand; also, brush; --
called also <altname>scrub brush</altname>. See <er>Brush</er>,
above.</def> <mark>[Australia & South Africa]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Forestry)</fld> <def>A low, straggling tree of
inferior quality.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Scrub bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an
Australian passerine bird of the family <fam>Atrichornithidae</fam>, as
<spn>Atrichia clamosa</spn>; -- called also <altname>brush
bird</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Scrub oak</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>,
<cd>the popular name of several dwarfish species of oak. The scrub oak
of New England and the Middle States is <spn>Quercus ilicifolia</spn>, a
scraggy shrub; that of the Southern States is a small tree (<spn>Quercus
Catesbaei</spn>); that of the Rocky Mountain region is <spn>Quercus
undulata</spn>, var. <varn>Gambelii</varn>.</cd> -- <col><b>Scrub
robin</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an Australian singing bird of
the genus <gen>Drymodes</gen>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrub</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Scrub
<hw>Scrub</hw> <pr>(skr⟦ucr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mean; dirty;
contemptible; scrubby.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How solitary, how <qex>scrub</qex>, does this town look!</q>
<rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No little <qex>scrub</qex> joint shall come on my board.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Scrub game</b></col>, <cd>a game, as of ball, by
unpracticed players.</cd> -- <col><b>Scrub race</b></col>, <cd>a race
between scrubs, or between untrained animals or
contestants.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrubbed</ent>⟦br⟧
